In his work &quot;The Republic&quot; Plato put forward his thesis that a totalitarian state composed of three classes: philosophers, warriors and the common folk could remain in a fixed and ideal state ruled by a philosopher-king. In other words: philosophy would rule society. This idea has remained very strong up through today.<br>
Yet Plato utterly failed in the Sicilian city-state Syracuse falling prey to all kinds of factional infighting and eventually having to escape from slavery. After this philosophers dwelt almost permanently on how imperfect humans were in comparison with their Perfect Ideas.<br>
In that sense I regret that Plato failed. His rigid policies would have met with some success first but ultimately I think they would have led te defeat for Syracuse. How would that have impacted Plato's philosophical reputation?<br>
I would speculate negatively, other philosophers would be more sceptical toward his political theories. Maybe they would even doubt his theory on the Perfect Ideas. That would open the way to more historical, proto-evolutionist theories such as those of Heraclitus of Ephesos.<br>
Although the idea that as a philosopher you're prefect and the only one able to rule would still be attractive maybe they would have been more practical, more (proto)evolution-minded. That would have sped up the development of civilization and prevented some of our modern-day tragedies such as Stalin. <br>
Indeed the idea of computer-controlled planning is still very much alive in the minds of Eurocrats. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :jedi --><img src=http://www.smilies-world.de/Smilies/Smilies_boese_1/lsabre.gif ALT=":jedi"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>spacefaring rodent</span><br>  Posts: 1135<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/13/03 1:31 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=34.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/extern/935754.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: What if Plato had succeeded?</span><hr size=1> I never was a big fan of Plato's philosophy.  He hated democracy and thought that proper rulership meant having a &quot;philosopher king&quot; in power who wouldn't allow the mere mortal men beneath him to have any say in how the State was run on the grounds that they were too stupid to know what was good for themselves.  He definately put state &quot;rights&quot; above individual rights, if he even respected any kind of individual rights at all.  Considering that Plato believed wholly in the right of rulers to engage in censorship, take people's children away from them automatically on the grounds that the state can raise them better, refuse medical treatment to certain types of individuals, and a thousand other things, I just don't think his ideal society would have lasted long.  In my opinion the best society is that which allows the free flow of ideas, limits the power of its government, and  respects individual rights above state rights.  Perhaps I'm just living in that cave Plato was so fond of talking about but I can't say I'd flock to live in any country that was being ruled by Plato.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :satansmoke --><img src=http://www.smilies-world.de/Smilies/Smilies_klein_1/sasmokin.gif ALT=":satansmoke"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nuclaeon>Nuclaeon</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 146<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/13/03 3:01 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=34.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: What if Plato had succeeded?</span><hr size=1> I think the one disadvantage to democracy is its inability to deal with long problems with unpopular solutions.  People don't want to do what hurts them in the short term, and this can be a problem.  This is, I feel, where ultimately democracy will fail.<br>
<br>
Perhaps a good technological solution to this in the future is having artificial intelligence manage day to day affairs and make decisions in the best interests of humanity.  Of course, a society has every right to override any decision made by the AI units. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=markix@nuclearspace>MarkIX</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Hotel Magnate</span><br>  Posts: 129<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/13/03 3:08 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=34.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: What if Plato had succeeded?</span><hr size=1> If people can't make decisions for them selves in their own best interests why do you think a computer Programmed by those same people would be any different ? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nuclaeon>Nuclaeon</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 147<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/13/03 3:40 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=34.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: What if Plato had succeeded?</span><hr size=1> Because people are swayed by their own ideologies.  They have not the time nor the resources to evaluate every issue in a cost-benefit fashion that is merited.  An AI unit can collect data and evaluate the costs and benefits of a policy to society with much less effort than humans can.  Also, people are corruptable whereas computers (properly supervised) are not. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td n