<br>
I doubt whether having AI would solve the problem once and for all. You're right in that the people of Plato's time were too individualistic too make his State feasible on a long-term basis. <br>
Yet his basic idea and yours is all wrong: Prefect Ideas that can be used as an absolute scale to measure the imperfect state of nature. These belong to what the 19th century thinker Herbert Spencer called &quot;the Unknowable&quot; (religious territory not scientific). Instead philosophers should focus on &quot;the Knowable&quot;, the state of nature as it has evolved over the billions of years of evolution. <br>
The Unknowable (or Plato's cave) cannot be penetrated by reason and consequentially not by Artificial Intelligence. Hence we need to discover the Knowable by finding out through trial-and-error. Stumbling through instead of having a philosopher-king dictating his version of the Unknowable would then be more adaptive to a society.<br>
